[normal]Q86 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Garnier[bold]:[bold] Thank you. Can I turn to Spencer Dale? You have been a bit quiet for a bit. Can I talk to stressed households, and the problems we are getting with stressed 
[normal]households? We have heard a bit earlier that 60% of GDP comes from household consumption
[normal],
[normal] and we have recently had a report that has been published by the Centre for Social Justice called 
[normal]Maxed Out
[normal] that looks at household debt and household problems where it notes one or two things. Only 
[normal]Ireland
[normal] has a higher ratio of personal debt to GDP among European countries than the 
[normal]UK
[normal], which obviously puts us in a very bad position. How dangerous do you think this high level of household debt is to the recovery in the future?
[normal]Spencer Dale[bold]: I think it reflects an increased vulnerability to economic shocks. The balance sheet of the household sector as a whole is relatively healthy, but within there are distributions where some people have very high levels of debt and others very high levels of savings. The vulnerability is with the people who have the high level of debt. To a very large extent those increases in debt are a counterpart to the increase in house prices we saw prior to the financial crisis
[normal],
[normal] where what we saw were young households having to take out mortgages to pay for their houses. The recipients of that were old households who then saved that money, which is why the balance sheet as a whole was relatively strong but where we do have these pockets of vulnerability associated with high levels of debt.
[normal]Q87 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Garnier[bold]:[bold] There was another report that was out during the summer where it looks at the financial buffers that households had
[normal],
[normal] and the financial buffers for those households between 24 and 44 years old is just an eight-day buffer, whereas as you so rightly said pensioners
[normal],
[normal] I think
[normal],
[normal] is a 175-day buffer, but then of course you would expect that because they have their savings and their pension. Clearly
[normal],
[normal] we have this colossal amount of household debt at a time when interest rates are at a super
[normal]-
[normal]low level
[normal],
[normal] and we can see them going back to a low level of interest rate with a three, four, five, six-fold increase in the base rate. What sort of effect do you think that is going to have on the recovery?
[normal]Spencer Dale[bold]: The level of household debt as a proportion of income has fallen over the last few years, so it has come back a little bit but still remains high.
[normal]Mark [bold]Garnier[bold]:[bold] Yes, it has come from 175%—
[normal]Spencer Dale[bold]: The levels of arrears and defaults at the moment are also at very low levels. The issue is when interest rates start to rise the implications that will have, and I have a somewhat nervousness at some of these studies. They always say, “If interest rates were to go up tomorrow that would have very significant implications
[normal].
[normal]” Yes, it would, and that is the whole point of forward guidance. We are not going to raise interest rates tomorrow. We are going to raise them at a time when the economy is significantly 
[normal]stronger,
[normal] employment levels are higher, when incomes are higher. My hope is by following that the household sector, along with the corporate sector, will be in a better position to withstand a rise in interest rates when we do so. We are very aware of this issue when raising interest rates, and we will make sure that we take that into account in terms of the pace and speed with which we raise rates.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q88 [bold]&#xa0; 
