[normal] or they are just there because they have always been there. Thank you.
[normal]Dr Carney[bold]: Okay
[normal]; u
[normal]nderstood
[normal]. T
[normal]hank you.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q125 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Good afternoon. I would just like to ask you, Mr Bean, going back to forward guidance for a moment, in your October speech you said that it might be worth looking at changing the unemployment threshold for forward guidance. Can you just expand on that slightly? What sort of scenarios were you thinking of and what sort of level?
[normal]Charles Bean[bold]: Let me be accurate
[normal].
[normal] I was not saying that we would change the guidance that we provided. What I was saying is that as we approach the threshold, clearly there would be—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q126 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Sorry, can I just remind you exactly what you said? You said there was scope for, “resetting the unemployment threshold to a new lower level”.
[normal]Charles Bean[bold]: Yes, I will expand on it. It is not resetting it now, but as we get to the threshold, there will be a question about what comes afterwards
[normal],
[normal] and there will obviously be debate going on in the markets and possibly this Committee and so forth about, “Are we going to raise interest rates?” or whatever. We will have learnt quite a lot over the journey to 7%, as the Governor said earlier on. I would expect, as the 
[normal]c
[normal]ommittee gets close to that 7% threshold, it will feel in a better position to give some indication about what is likely to happen next, whether that will involve raising bank rate or possibly it may well be the case that because productivity has recovered, inflation pressures remain low, that it will look as if it is plausible and sensible to keep the bank rate where it is at the moment. It will be perfectly possible for the 
[normal]c
[normal]ommittee in that case to issue new guidance once it has hit the 7% to say that they expect to be able to maintain it until 6.5%. It is worth emphasising I am not saying changing the existing guidance, but it is about there may be guidance that comes after where we are.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q127 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Thank you. Dr Broadbent, as the external policeman of the MPC, if I can call you that, can I ask you, do you think that forward guidance was in part driven by a desire to avoid a potential collapse of the bond markets following what happened in the States, when they talked about perhaps slowing down QE and there was a big run on the bonds? Certainly
[normal],
[normal] Governor King came to this Committee and made very clear it is a long time before we start raising interest rates. Was forward guidance in part simply to calm the nerves of the markets and therefore is there a risk that we, as the Treasury Committee, should be concerned 
[normal]that you may keep moving the goalposts in order to keep the markets calm because of the risk that
[normal],
[normal] in raising interest rates, you have to start to address the unwinding of QE and thereby spark a run on the bond markets?
[normal]Dr Broadbent[bold]: There are several aspects to that. I would say to some extent
[normal],
[normal] yes, I certainly hope that guidance would prevent premature excessive increases in interest rates. Indeed, I think they already have, measurably so. As the Governor said earlier, not so much to calm the markets
[normal]—
[normal]it is not always out of control
[normal]—
[normal]but you would normally have seen in response both to stronger direct evidence of growth, and indeed the upgrade in our own growth forecast, a slightly higher rise in forward interest rates. Clearly
[normal],
[normal] it would not be desirable to present something that was wholly unwarranted, whether it is what happened in June in the United States of this year, or indeed 20 years ago, 1994, when the bond market reacted very adversely to the first rise in interest rates.
[normal]When it comes to the point when the Asset Purchase Facility starts to be wound down, I can see guidance of some description
[normal]; 
[normal]in other words, a little more precision about the conditions under which it would happen and how we would do it would be desirable. Of course, we are a long, long way from that.
[normal]Can I just caveat all that by saying that we 
[normal]could not and certainly would
[normal] not seek to micro-control interest rate markets beyond that. Guidance should not be mistaken—and I tried to point this out in the speech, but I think a lot of the coverage still misses this point—as an unconditional promise. It was never that
[normal];
[normal] it is not that
[normal];
[normal] and we are not seeking at all points in time to control the entire yield curve regardless of economic conditions. That would be foolish.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q128 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] I understand, but can I just ask you a further question then, because it does concern me that when we get to the point where we are unwinding the asset purchase programme then inevitably there is suddenly a big seller of gilts in the market, so what that inevitably means is a change in the yield curve, a change in market sentiment and so on. Can forward guidance be used? Are there any means at your disposal to be able to control the impact on the markets?
[normal]Dr Broadbent[bold]: Let me just challenge the word “inevitable”. It is not going to happen arbitrarily. If I had to guess about the circumstances under which the unwind would happen, it would be an environment in which the economy was growing more strongly, in which the demand for liquidity was falling, in which the Government borrowing requirements were also falling, and all those things would tend to go in the opposite direction
[normal];
[normal] they would tend to depress gilts. We would be not suddenly deciding whimsically, “Now we are going to get rid of it all
[normal].
[normal]” We would be doing it at a time in which I think the economy could absorb these sales of gilts. The demand for gilts would be going up and the supply from the Government would be falling, so it is not inevitable.
[normal]Having said that, the example you raised earlier of the United States in the summer of this year
[normal]—
[normal]just a suggestion not even of a sale, but a slight change in the rate of purchase
[normal]—
[normal]that was instructive and it is clearly important to communicate very clearly as best one can the conditions under which this would happen and how it would happen. It is, as I say, some way away yet. Remember that we have said we would not countenance reducing the size of the facility at least until interest rates start to go up, so it is some way off yet, but I—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q129 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] But can I just remind you
[normal]—
[normal]you will recall Governor King specifically said how it would be unwound is there would be a 0.25% rise in base rate and then the Asset Purchase Facility would be unwound
[normal]?
[normal]Dr Broadbent[bold]: I do not think he did say that.
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] He said that in this Committee some years ago.
[normal]Charles Bean[bold]: Yes, I was going to say he did not say it would be a quarter of a point increase and then we would immediately start—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q130 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] No, not immediately. No, he said the next step, there would be a change in direction by a small tightening, perhaps 0.25%, and afterwards, instead of further 
[normal]tightenings
[normal] of interest rates, the Asset Purchase Facility would be unwound. It is etched in my memory, but we can check the record.
[normal]Dr Carney[bold]: Can we etch something else in your memory?
[normal]Charles Bean[bold]: Yes.
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Yes, please do.
[normal]Charles Bean[bold]: Certainly
[normal],
[normal] the vision here is that we would not embark on sales of the gilts until it was quite clear that the economy was on a sustained recovery path where we needed to keep on gradually tightening the stance of monetary policy. Now, that might well not happen when we just 
[normal]raised
[normal] by 25 basis points. You might wait until the bank rate had gone up a few notches before we felt that things were sufficiently tranquil and well-entrenched to make a steady sale at a reasonably slow pace back to the market of the gilts sensible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q131 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Okay, thank you. Mr Dale, as the economist to the 
[normal]B
[normal]ank, can you just comment
[normal]?
[normal] 
[normal] I
[normal]n the 
[normal]eurozone
[normal], Mr Bean in his recent speech—I do not want to ask him again, because I have not given you a turn—he said that a lot will depend on the ECB’s stress tests of the European banks as to how well they are able to sustain their recovery. Obviously
[normal],
[normal] we all agree that their fate is very much tied in with our own, since there is a huge amount of trade between us, yet Mr Bean also made the point that the 
[normal]eurozone
[normal] remains a huge risk to the 
[normal]UK
[normal] economy. Can you comment on to what extent can the 
[normal]eurozone
[normal] ever reduce the risk that it is to the 
[normal]UK
[normal] economy until it achieves proper banking union? Is it feasible that the risks can be lowered without them moving to their end game of fiscal union?
[normal]Spencer Dale[bold]: I think you can reduce the risk. They can do all sorts of things to help reduce the risk in terms of putting infrastructures in place like the stress tests, which increase confidence, by the countries in the periphery undertaking some of the adjustments and gradually doing the rebalancing they need to take place. Charlie should speak for himself in terms of his own speech, but my own view is
[normal],
[normal] under the best possible case, the euro area is going to grow pretty weakly over the next few years and will not help and not be a driver for growth for our economy. Whatever they do, there will be a significant risk over that period of time of worse outcomes, and so we should think of the euro area as a persistent drag on our economy for a sustained period, but that does not mean the risk cannot get less as they gradually go through that adjustment process.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q132 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Following on from that, do you think that you can have a successful currency without a common fiscal policy?
[normal]Spencer Dale[bold]: I think there 
[normal]are
[normal] many different ways that you can structure that
[normal];
[normal] and ultimately
[normal],
[normal] they are political decisions rather than economic ones.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q133 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Yes, but as an economist, can you tell us whether you can have a successful single currency, the euro, unless you have a shared fiscal policy over the medium to long term?
[normal]Spencer Dale[bold]: I think there are circumstances in which you can and circumstances you cannot
[normal];
[normal] and ultimately
[normal],
[normal] they are political ones rather than economic ones.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q134 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Governor, just bearing in mind today that the Scottish Parliament have come out with their proposal that they can continue to keep the pound but have two entirely separate fiscal policies, what is the central thinking of the Bank of England about how to cope with two openly and very deliberately different fiscal policies
[normal],
[normal] while trying to squeeze into the one
[normal]-
[normal]size
[normal]-
[normal]fits
[normal]-
[normal]all pound?
[normal]Dr Carney[bold]: As you can appreciate, the release of, from my understanding, 600 or 700 pages of documents occurred during this Committee. I have been riveted in my attention to the Committee, so I would at least ask leave to read the documents.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q135 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] But you must have some thoughts on this. It is not new.
[normal]Dr Carney[bold]: I would say there are many lessons from the crisis period that reinforce attributes of the most sustainable currency unions
[normal],
[normal] and it is difficult in the fullness of time to have a currency union, and I speak from the Canadian experience, without some element of fiscal federalism. My personal view for the 
[normal]eurozone
[normal]—and I will speak only to the 
[normal]eurozone
[normal]—is that there will be a requirement of some form of fiscal federalism. I will use that term
[normal]—
[normal]there are politer terms
[normal]—
[normal]but the banking union that you referred to, which shares liabilities and exposure, is a form of fiscal federalism, but I suspect that ultimately in the fullness of time that will have to be reinforced by some element of sharing, potentially through the labour market, potentially through other mechanisms, in order to have a fully viable euro.
[normal]Chair:[bold] We can only take one last very quick one.
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] I have to choose then, don’t I? I am going to choose the question that is going to get me into a lot of trouble with the Chairman.
[normal]Chair:[bold] I know what it is, and you will not be in trouble.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q136 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrea [bold]Leadsom[bold]:[bold] Governor, in your five months 
